  "prompt": "In watchos menu is not opened by force touching on interface controller why?",
  "response": "In watchOS, the traditional force touch (or 3D Touch) gesture for opening menus has been deprecated. Here are the key points and alternatives:\n\n1. Deprecation:\n- Apple deprecated force touch in watchOS 7\n- Force touch is no longer recommended or supported in newer versions of watchOS\n\n2. Recommended Alternatives:\n```swift\n// Use standard navigation or action sheets\n- Navigation between views\n- Contextual menus\n- Action sheets\n- Buttons with clear actions\n```\n\n3. Migration Example:\n```swift\n// Old Force Touch Method (Deprecated)\noverride func contextMenu() {\n    // Force touch menu logic\n}\n\n// New Recommended Approach\n@objc func showContextMenu() {\n    let alertController = UIAlertController(\n        title: \"Options\",\n        message: nil,\n        preferredStyle: .actionSheet\n    )\n    \n    alertController.addAction(UIAlertAction(\n        title: \"Option 1\", \n        style: .default, \n        handler: { _ in \n            // Handle option 1 \n        }\n    ))\n    \n    alertController.addAction(UIAlertAction(\n        title: \"Cancel\", \n        style: .cancel, \n        handler: nil\n    ))\n    \n    present(alertController, animated: true)\n}\n```\n\n4. Design Guidelines:\n- Use explicit buttons\n- Create clear navigation paths\n- Utilize standard iOS/watchOS UI patterns\n\n5. SwiftUI Alternative:\n```swift\nstruct ContentView: View {\n    var body: some View {\n        Menu(\"Options\") {\n            Button(\"Action 1\") { }\n            Button(\"Action 2\") { }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBest practice is to redesign your interface to use standard navigation and interaction methods instead of relying on force touch.",
